<subsection xml:id="subsec-fractional-indices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Fractional indices</title>
    <p>
        Fractional indices, also known as rational indices, are used to represent roots of numbers in index form. 
        A fractional index indicates that the base is raised to a power and then the root is taken.
    </p>
    <p>
        For example, if we have a base <m>a</m> and a fractional index <m>\frac{m}{n}</m>, it can be expressed as:
        <m>a^{\frac{m}{n}} = \sqrt[n]{a^m}</m>.
        This means that we first raise <m>a</m> to the power of <m>m</m> and then take the <m>n</m>-th root of the result.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                
            </p>
           
            <p>
               1. In groups of <m>5</m>, investigate what happens when a number is raised to a fractional exponent.
            </p>
            <p>
                2. Consider the number<m>(25)^{1/2}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
               2. Express it as a product of its prime factors in index form i.e  <m>25 = 5^2</m>, so <m>25^{1/2}= (5^2)^{1/2}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
               3. Apply the law of indices to simplify the above.
            </p>
            <p>
               4. Now, work out the following: 
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           <m>8^{2/3}</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>81^{3/4}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>27^{1/3}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                5. Discuss your work with your classmates.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
              Evaluate:  
            </p>
            <p>
               a) <m>16^{3/4}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
               b) <m>4^{-1/2}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
               a) First, express  <m>16^{3/4}</m> as a product of its prime factors: 
            </p>
            <p>
                 <m>16^{3/4} = (4^2)^{3/4}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Multiplying powers in <m>(4^2)^{3/4}</m>, we have:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>2 \times \frac{3}{4} = \frac{3}{2}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, <m>(4^2)^{3/4} = (4)^{3/2}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                This is the same as <m>(\sqrt{4})^3 = 2^3</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                b) For  <m>4^{-1/2}</m>, we have:
            </p>
            <p>
                  <m>4^{-1/2} = (2^2)^{-1/2}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
               Multiplying powers we have: <m>2 \times -\frac{1}{2} = -1</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Hence we have: <m>2^{-1}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
               Since <m>2^{-1}</m> is equivalent to <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, <m>16^{3/4} = \frac{1}{2}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    
</subsection>